          "title": "Succession installed — the covenant community moves forward",
          "body": "The transition from Moses to Joshua occupies only one verse (34:9) but it carries the full theological weight of Numbers 27:18-23 and Deuteronomy 31:1-8 behind it. Joshua was already equipped before Moses died — the spirit of wisdom had been imparted through the laying-on of hands in advance. The community's response — 'the sons of Israel listened to him and did as the LORD had commanded Moses' (34:9) — is remarkable: their obedience to Joshua is explicitly framed as obedience to Moses's own prior command. The standard does not change with the servant. This is the Pentateuch's answer to the pastoral anxiety that accompanies every great transition: the word of the LORD does not die when its primary human instrument does. What changes is the hand that holds the pen; what does not change is the text being written. Peter Davids and others in the wisdom tradition note that the 'spirit of wisdom' language (ruach chokhmah, 34:9) anticipates the Spirit-endowed leadership of David's line (Isa. 11:2) and ultimately of the messianic servant — the succession chain points far beyond Joshua."
